defaultWritten evidence from Eddie Gerrard (TIC 076)
defaultThe purpose of this short report is to bring to the attention of the Transport Committee the real difficulties that are being experienced in the Broadwindsor
default group of parishes, the possible solutions and the consequences if there are no solutions taken up.
defaultMy name is Eddie Gerrard, This year I stood in the County Council Elections, in the Beaminster area. In doing so I visited over 1,300 homes, gaining a great
default deal of information and many ideas. My specific comments relate to Drimpton and Greenham, with further general comments about the Beaminster area, in West Dorset.  It consists of a collection of villages, hamlets, and farms, lying on the borders of Somers
defaultet and Devon, roughly bounded by the rivers Synderford and Axe. Its landscape is one which all would recognise as quintessentially traditional England.  A patchwork of hedgerows, fields, lanes, villages and farms, deep valleys and rounded hills, with a dis
defaulttant view of the sea from its highest places.  The parish is within close reach of the historic market towns of Beaminster, Bridport, and Crewkerne.  In 2012, the time the Parish Plan was produced there were just over 1,300 residents.  At the time of writi
defaultng the report there were about 30 children below the age of 4 and 30 men and women over the age of 90 years. The Broadwindsor Parishes are made up of Broadwindsor which includes Drimpton, and Burstock which includes blackdown and Seaborough. 
defaultOne of the ma
defaultjor issues that people raised on the doorsteps was public transport or to be more precise the lack of it.
